commentBody:
@AKGirl
You’re most welcome. Some people know chickpeas well and some do not, especially if they’re new cooks and we should always encourage new cooks. Others grow up only hearing and knowing one name for ceci beans. Labeling can be so irregular in supermarkets and on food packaging. 

Yesterday at Trader Joe’s I saw a handwritten sign by the canned beans stating “chickpeas are also called garbanzo beans!”.  It’s clearly confusing for many shoppers and store employees.

@Jen. I googled it and found about 10 ways with the easiest and best requiring a food processor.  If you have one,  cool the mixture and pour it into a ziploc bag. Then freeze it in the bag.  Take frozen mixture out of bag (mine was ready in 2-3 hours and not frozen solid) and break into chunks.  Put chunks in processor.  Then pulse it or mix to “churn” the ice cream.  It became a nice creamy texture which I poured into a glass container to then freeze overnight. 

I had cut alcohol in half as didn’t have enough but added some of the pulpier discard from juicing as orange juice “concentrate” which was suggested as a non alcoholic substitute for the Grand Marnier.  Worked fine. One comment here mentioned that without the alcohol it would not scoop. The end product scooped just fine for me after letting it defrost a bit just like any other store bought ice cream. The consistency was between sorbet and ice cream.   Came out refreshing and light tasting. 

Next time, I may halve the granulated sugar.

@VSB if you turn the oven on when you start, it will take you about 10 minutes to make the lemon curd to set aside to cool to room temperature.
If you then start mixing the cake batter it will take less than 10 minutes  to put in the oven- which will be ready. 
Both the lemon curd and cake will need to cool a few hours before continuing.

@T Schu
Funny, I see the same question is asked and answered a couple of times. The answer given says no because honey is an invert sugar. 
Since I always have maple syrup on hand and not the the suggested substitutes, I may just try it anyway and see. I have a maple pecan pie recipe that is delicious. The flavors of those two tree products go together so well.

@Margaret
Good comment
Another reason to provide weight, I was just using a middle east cookbook and all herb quantities were provided in both volume and weight, weight is much faster

@Edith 

There is nothing like the taste and texture of garlic roasted in its skin. 

 As you eat you will find the cloves.  Try squeezing one or two onto a piece of a good baguette.

@Parisian Savoyarde 
Skins from any fruit or veg contain much of the nutrients it's known for; so by peeling you'll lose lotsa vitamins, minerals, etc but also the real flavor bombs and colors too! And yes textures, as well. 
So... Why bother removing them at all?!?

@Aviva
Did you refrigerate overnight before baking?  Did you get the chilled slices into a hot oven quickly? You want that oven preheated before you start slicing. 

Chilling the dough helps individual buttery or oily cookies hold their shape until they cook.
